The grammar’s two start‑symbol rules are  

1. S → NT82 NT22  
2. S → NT40 NT77  

Rule 2 would put the terminal produced by NT77 (t15) at the end of every generated string, but the target string contains no t15, so rule 2 cannot be used.

Rule 1 forces the very first token of any generated string to be the single terminal produced by NT82.  
NT82 has only terminal productions  
 NT82 → 't29' | NT82 → 't34'  

Hence every string derived via rule 1 must begin with t29 or t34.  
The given string begins with t12, not t29 or t34, so rule 1 is also impossible.

Since neither start‑symbol rule can yield the target string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in two ways:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
   NT82 has only the terminal productions NT82 → 't29' | 't34'.  
   Therefore the generated string must begin with t29 or t34.

2. S → NT40 NT77  
   NT77 has only the terminal production NT77 → 't15'.  
   Therefore the generated string must end with t15.

The given string starts with t17 (not t29/t34) and ends with t31 (not t15), so it cannot match either pattern. Hence it cannot be derived from the grammar.

No

To be generated, the string must be derived from one of the two start productions:  

1. S → NT82 NT22  
2. S → NT40 NT77  

Case 2 would make the very last symbol of the string the single terminal produced by NT77, namely ‘t15’.  
The given string ends with ‘t34’, so Case 2 is impossible.

For Case 1 the string would be the concatenation of what NT82 produces followed by what NT22 produces.  
NT82 can only produce the single terminals ‘t29’ or ‘t34’; therefore NT22 would have to generate the remaining 18 or 18 (19‑1) symbols.

But NT22’s only productions are  

NT22 → NT71 NT48 (length 2)  
NT22 → NT68 NT97 (length 2)  
NT22 → ‘t23’   (length 1)  
NT22 → ‘t12’   (length 1)

so NT22 can yield at most 2 terminals, never 18. Hence Case 1 is also impossible.

Since neither start production can yield a 19‑symbol string matching the one supplied, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
   – NT82 produces exactly one terminal, either t29 or t34.  
   – Therefore the first word of the string would have to be t29 or t34.  
   – The given string starts with t49. Hence this option fails immediately.

2. S → NT40 NT77  
   – NT77 produces exactly one terminal, t15.  
   – Thus the last word of the string would have to be t15.  
   – The given string ends with t31. Hence this option also fails.

Since neither of the only two possible top‑level derivations matches the first or last token of the supplied string, no derivation from S can yield the entire 22‑token string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
2. S → NT40 NT77

NT77 produces exactly the single terminal t15, so alternative 2 would require the whole string to end with the single token t15 – it actually ends with t9, so this alternative is impossible.

Hence we must use alternative 1, splitting the string into a prefix generated by NT82 and a suffix generated by NT22.

Examine what NT22 can generate:

• NT22 → 't23' (single token)  
• NT22 → 't12' (single token)  
• NT22 → NT71 NT48  
• NT22 → NT68 NT97

Every production on the right‑hand side of NT22 can ultimately yield only the terminals
t23, t12, t36, t5, t15, t21, t48, t35, t9, t0, t38, t31, t8, t29, or t10.  
The only grammar symbol that ever produces the terminal t28 is NT40, and NT40 never occurs in any derivation headed by NT22. Therefore NT22 can never generate a string containing t28.

The given string contains the terminal t28 three times (positions 3, 4 and 24). Whichever split we choose between the NT82 part and the NT22 part, the NT22 suffix would have to include at least one of those t28 tokens, which is impossible.

Consequently the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only two binary productions:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
   NT82 is limited to the single‑terminal productions  
   NT82 → 't29' | 't34'  
   Hence NT82 contributes exactly one token and that token must be the very first symbol of any string derived with this rule (because the right‑hand side contains only NT82 followed by NT22).

2. S → NT40 NT77  
   NT77 has the single‑terminal production  
   NT77 → 't15'  
   Therefore any string derived with this rule must end with the terminal t15.

Now examine the given 33‑token string:

t48 t10 t5 t9 t21 t6 t5 t0 t10 t31 t39 t39 t29 t36 t38 t28 t39 t39 t40 t40 t35 t15 t39 t17 t34 t35 t9 t10 t29 t8 t10 t36 t49

• The first token is t48, which is neither t29 nor t34, so the derivation S → NT82 NT22 is impossible.

• The last token is t49, not t15, so the derivation S → NT40 NT77 is impossible.

Since S has no other productions, no derivation can produce the given string.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in two ways:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
   • NT82 produces a single terminal, either t29 or t34.  
   • Therefore the first symbol of any string in the language must be t29 or t34.

2. S → NT40 NT77  
   • NT77 produces a single terminal, t15.  
   • Therefore the last symbol of any string in the language must be t15.

The given string begins with t33 (not t29 or t34) and ends with t38 (not t15). Consequently it cannot match either of the only two possible shapes that a sentence derived from S can have.

Hence the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT82 NT22  
   NT82 can produce only a single terminal, either t29 or t34.  
   Therefore any sentence derived via this rule must begin with t29 or t34.  
   The given string begins with t33, so this alternative is impossible.

2. S → NT40 NT77  
   NT77 produces exactly one terminal, t15.  
   Hence any sentence derived via this rule must end with t15.  
   The given string ends with t48, so this alternative is also impossible.

Since neither of the only two possibilities for S can match the first and last tokens of the provided string, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only two productions for the start symbol are  

1. S → NT82 NT22  
2. S → NT40 NT77  

For any derivation, the first terminal of the string must come from the left‐most non‑terminal in these productions.

1. NT82 can only produce the terminals t29 or t34, so a sentence derived with production (1) must start with t29 or t34 – not with t0.

2. NT40 can produce
   • t28  
   • t39  
   • NT97 NT0   → t48 …  
   • NT15 NT71 → t49 …
   In every case, the first terminal produced is t28, t39, t48 or t49 – never t0.

Since the given string begins with t0, neither start‑production can generate it. Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.
